== Numerical Model <numerical-model>
In the following section a self developed model, which takes the
induction law into account, is presented. First, we consider the
movement of the pod with the general law of movement
$ v_0 = dv(x, t) arrow.l.r.double dd(t) = frac(dd(x), v_0) $ The
differential form of the magnetic flux is given as
$ dd(Phi) = vb(A) dot.op dd(vb(B)) + vb(B) dot.op dd(vb(A)) $
but since the cross-section does not change, we can simplify the
equation to $ dd(Phi) = vb(A) dot.op dd(vb(B)) $

We consider a small cross-section here which is given as
$A = l med dd(x)$, with $l$ as the width of the rail. So the induced
voltage in the rail is given by Faraday's law of induction
$ V_(upright(i n d)) = - dv(Phi, t) = - dv(Phi, x) v_0 = - pdv(B, x) med l med v_0 med dd(x) $
Together with Ohm's law, we can calculate the current density in the
rail
$ j = I / A = frac(V_(upright(i n d)), R med A) = pdv(B, x) v_0 1 / rho dd(x) $
A volume element can be described by $dd(V) = h med l med dd(x)$, so the
induced B-field can be expressed by the Biot-Savart law as follows
$ B_(upright(i)) (x) = frac(mu, 4 pi) frac(h med l, rho) v_0 integral_(- oo)^(+ oo) pdv(B, x)\|_(x') 1 / (x - x ')^2 dd(x, 2)' $
Here the magnetic field $B$ is the superposition of applied and induced
field, i.e. $B = B_0 + B_i$. Since the induced field depends on itself
an analytical solution is difficult and not yet found by the author. To
solve this equation we follow a numerical Ansatz: at a first step, $B$
is calculated only by the external field $B_0$. Then an iteration
follows, which calculates the magnetic field regarding the induced field
from the former step. \
At the end the converged $B_i$ and the applied Field are added to
retrieve the resulting field.
